        {
            "id": "when_to_use_sets",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**When should you use sets?**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Use sets when you need to store **unique items** only, remove duplicates from a list, or check membership very quickly."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "removing_duplicates_example",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A common use case is removing duplicates from a list by converting it to a set."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can pass the list `numbers` to the `set()` function to convert it to a set. The result is a set of unique numbers."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4]\nunique = set(numbers)\nprint(unique)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "{1, 2, 3, 4}"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Converting the list to a set automatically removed all duplicates."
                }
            ]
        },
